{"title": "â€˜Avatar 3â€™ to Rule Over Christmas Box Office; â€˜Anacondaâ€™ to Top Fellow New Holiday Releases â€˜Marty Supremeâ€™ and â€˜Song Sung Blueâ€™", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/film/box-office/christmas-box-office-avatar-3-marty-supreme-song-sung-blue-anaconda-projections-1236614973/", "summary": "Theater owners are preparing for a very merry Christmas season. This holiday might not be one for the record books, but the lineup of films offers something important &#8212; a range of genres and styles &#8212; as exhibitors brace for what&#8217;s usually the busiest stretch of the year. That&#8217;s an important distinction in post-COVID times. [&#8230;]", "content": "Theater owners are preparing for a very merry Christmas season.\n\nThis holiday might not be one for the record books, but the lineup of films offers something important â€” a range of genres and styles â€” as exhibitors brace for whatâ€™s usually the busiest stretch of the year. Thatâ€™s an important distinction in post-COVID times. Since the pandemic, cinema operators have relied on one billion-dollar behemoth (â€œSpider-Man: No Way Homeâ€ in 2021 and â€œAvatar: The Way of Waterâ€ in 2022) or struggled with none at all (â€œAquaman and the Lost Kingdomâ€ floundered in 2023 and while â€œMufasaâ€ rebounded after a soft start in 2024, â€œThe Lion Kingâ€ prequel couldnâ€™t claw its way to the billion-dollar mark).\n\nThis year, â€œAvatar: Fire and Ashâ€ will continue to dominate but James Cameronâ€™s sci-fi threequel wonâ€™t be alone in enticing audiences. Over the weekend, a trio of holiday releases â€” A24â€™s R-rated ping-pong adventure â€œMarty Supreme,â€ the Focus Features musical drama â€œSong Sung Blueâ€ and Sonyâ€™s disaster comedy â€œAnacondaâ€ â€” hope to cater to moviegoers young, old, or disinterested in returning to the alien planet of Pandora.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nâ€œAvatar: Fire and Ashâ€ is aiming for $55 million to $65 million over the traditional weekend and $75 million to $80 million through the four-day holiday frame. Those ticket sales would mark a 30% to 40% decline from its $89 million domestic debut. For context, â€œAvatar: The Way of Waterâ€ dropped by 52% in its sophomore outing after a significantly stronger $134 million debut. Disney and 20th Centuryâ€™s â€œAvatarâ€ franchise appears be experiencing diminishing returns, though itâ€™s important to remember these films arenâ€™t known for explosive opening weekends. Instead, â€œAvatarâ€ installments enjoy exceptional staying power, sticking around at the top of the box office for weeks on end. The first two films, which each ended up grossing over $2 billion globally, were No. 1 for seven consecutive weekends. Barring a surprise, â€œFire and Ashâ€ should remain atop the charts in North America well into the new year.\n\nIn terms of new releases, Jack Black and Paul Ruddâ€™s â€œAnacondaâ€ is expected to lead the pack with $20 million from 3,400 venues between Christmas on Thursday and Sunday. â€œMarty Supremeâ€ is targeting $12 million to $20 million, while â€œSong Song Blueâ€ is projected to earn $10 million to $14 million from 2,400 theaters. In general, Christmas releases donâ€™t always deliver huge debuts but tend to play and play on the big screen into January and beyond.\n\nâ€œAnacondaâ€ cost $45 million to produce. A meta-reboot, â€œAnacondaâ€ follows best friends who travel to the jungle to pursue their childhood dream of remaking their all-time favorite movie (you guessed it!) 1997â€™s â€œAnaconda.â€ The project starts to unravel when life imitates art and a real anaconda begins hunting them down.\n\nâ€œMarty Supremeâ€ had a rollicking start in limited release, breaking into the top 10 with $875,000 while playing on just six screens. Those initial returns are promising ahead of the nationwide expansion, which will test the $70 million-budgeted filmâ€™s commercial viability. It helps that TimothÃ©e Chalamet, who stars as the fictional table tennis champ Marty Mauser, has been rewriting the rules of movie marketing in terms of getting out the word for an original film. â€œMarty Supremeâ€ has generated great reviews and encouraging word of mouth. Now the question is: Will Chalametâ€™s viral antics translate to ticket sales?\n\nâ€œSong Sung Blueâ€ carries a modest $30 million production budget. Craig Brewer directed the film, featuring Hugh Jackman and Kate Hudson in the true story of two down-on-their luck musicians who form a Neil Diamond tribute band. Varietyâ€™s chief film critic Owen Gleiberman praised â€œSong Sung Blueâ€ as â€œa winning pop nostalgia trip with a dark side.â€\n\nWith just two weeks to go, overall domestic revenues are hovering at $8.37 billion, just 1.3% ahead of last year and 22.4% behind 2019, according to Comscore. Itâ€™s been a wobbly year with several hits (â€œLilo & Stitch,â€ â€œZootopia 2,â€ â€œA Minecraft Movieâ€ and â€œDemon Slayer,â€ among others) but not enough to offset a number of big-budget flops (â€œMission: Impossible â€“ The Final Reckoningâ€ and â€œSnow White,â€ to name a few). Projections for 2025 were already revised down to $9 billion, but after a brutal fall season, even that milestone feels like a stretch. Will these holiday offerings be able to deliver, or is the box office doomed to fall short of $9 billion for the second consecutive year?", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 14:30:00 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T14:42:52.942238"}
{"title": "â€˜Davidâ€™ Review: Handsome Animation but Standard-Issue Storytelling in Faith-Based Holiday Hit", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/film/reviews/david-review-1236616493/", "summary": "If all you know or remember of the eponymous biblical character&#8217;s story is that he defeated a hulking giant with a humble slingshot, then &#8220;David&#8221; might have some surprises in store for you â€” chief among them, the fact that the film continues for a full hour after this famous, seemingly climactic showdown. But the [&#8230;]", "content": "If all you know or remember of the eponymous biblical characterâ€™s story is that he defeated a hulking giant with a humble slingshot, then â€œDavidâ€ might have some surprises in store for you â€” chief among them, the fact that the film continues for a full hour after this famous, seemingly climactic showdown. But the films of Angel Studios, by and large, are not for audiences only vaguely acquainted with the Bible, and this surprisingly slick animated feature will play best with viewers who can see its every narrative turn coming. That is a sizeable demographic: Released wide last weekend, Brent Dawes and Phil Cunninghamâ€˜s film overperformed notably at the box office, landing in the runner-up spot to â€œAvatar: Fire and Ash,â€ and aptly defeating relative toon Goliath â€œThe SpongeBob Movie: Search for SquarePants.â€\n\nThis is all a perfectly on-the-nose outcome for a tale preaching the message that one must never underestimate the modest and pious when theyâ€™re up against the wealthy and decadent. (Or whatever moral descriptor applies to SpongeBob.) But â€œDavidâ€ attains its success by cribbing from the playbook of far mightier animation houses: There are shades here of Disney and DreamWorks â€” the latterâ€™s scripture-based hit â€œThe Prince of Egypt,â€ in particular â€” in everything from the filmâ€™s character design to its original song score, making for a proficient family entertainment thatâ€™s nonetheless a little too precision-engineered to feel truly stirring. Faith, â€œDavidâ€ has in spades; soul, not so much.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nWith Pixar-wide eyes and a mop of intricately tousled, treacle-brown hair, the young David (voiced by Brandon Engman) presents here as a plucky, intrepid moppet in the typical cartoon-hero mold. Heâ€™s introduced as a keen musician and lowly shepherdâ€™s son, dutifully minding his fatherâ€™s flock on the outskirts of Bethlehem, before swiftly launching into his generic â€œI wantâ€ song, the first of several peppily template-based but swiftly forgettable compositions by Grammy-winning Christian artist Jonas Myrin. Like any cutely drawn protagonist in his position, he yearns for bigger things, though he gets more than he bargained for when â€” after valiantly protecting his sheep from a preying lion â€” heâ€™s summoned before the Prophet Samuel (Brian Stivale), who anoints the nonplussed lad the future king of Israel.\n\nMeanwhile, the present king, the insecure and short-tempered Saul (Adam Michael Gold), is facing rejection by God and a declaration of war by preening Philistine monarch King Achish (British comedian Asim Chaudhry, offering something of a throwback to limp-wristed comic stereotypes). Enter David, brought into Saulâ€™s court to soothe the kingâ€™s anxieties with his deft lyre-playing, though the tyke soon proves an unexpected military asset: Cue the famed face-off against Goliath, which is quite dazzlingly staged in a vast field of scarlet poppies, petals spraying like confetti when the iceberg-sized monster hits the ground.\n\nTaking place around the 50-minute mark, this scene proves both the narrative and aesthetic peak of a film that, clocking in at an indifferently paced 110 minutes, could test the patience of younger children. Everything that happens after, as David grows into a strapping, stout-hearted man (now voiced by Christian singer-songwriter Phil Wickham) and eventually challenges Saul for the throne that is rightly his, is checked off in fairly rote fashion. Expanding on their 2023 Angel Studios miniseries â€œYoung David,â€ Dawes and Cunningham obviously hew closely to the Book of Samuel â€” this isnâ€™t the genre for significant creative license â€” but also to the familiar rules of any Hollywood heroâ€™s journey.\n\nNone of which would be a debit if their David had a little more personality of his own, but he remains a stubbornly dull anchor for the film, bound by the generally humorless, declamatory tone of the writing. Supporting characters are similarly lacking in wit or detail, while the filmâ€™s vocal performances (save for Chaudhryâ€™s odd caricature) are adequate but not especially distinctive. It follows that the faces on screen are perhaps the least characterful element of the filmâ€™s generally impressive visual design.\n\nEverything around them, however, is vividly realized, and occasionally even inspired. â€œDavidâ€ is nothing if not a spectacular showcase for the technical capabilities of South African animation house Sunrise Productions â€” demonstrated here both at a large scale, in the palpably dusty, sun-scorched vistas of ancient Israel, and in small, supple glimmers of fire and water. One musical number, â€œTapestry,â€ registers as a standout not for the song but for its visual treatment amid a busy weaving workshop overhung by cotton-candy bales of pastel-dyed wool. Indeed, textiles are perhaps the most consistent marvel of â€œDavid,â€ as even the ecru hessian of the title characterâ€™s shepherding smock is rendered with textured, tactile specificity. Reveling in the material may go somewhat against the filmâ€™s principles, but respecting the little things does not.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 14:28:54 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T14:42:53.215189"}
